Builds the deterministic `bwrap` argv used to launch a sandboxed ("caged") process — the sole place that translates a `BwrapConfig` into actual bubblewrap CLI arguments. Output is a `Vec<OsString>` starting with `"bwrap"`, so callers invoke it via `Command::new(&argv[0]).args(&argv[1..])`.

Key invariant: `--unshare-net` is always present, unconditionally — the cage has no network access, and the only egress path is the API proxy socket bound in via `CAGE_RUN_DIR`. `--clearenv` is also unconditional, so `add_envs` must set every variable the caged command needs; nothing leaks from the host environment.

The workspace bind (`add_workspace`) is read-write at the target's *own real host path* — there is no fixed in-cage alias (referenced as ADR-046 elsewhere). Secret paths under the workspace are masked by binding `c.mask_file` (an empty file) read-only over each `c.secret_masks` entry — masked paths remain readable-as-empty rather than absent, since tools like git may stat/read them. This masking happens even though the surrounding workspace bind is writable, so mask order matters (masks must be applied after the base bind to take effect over it).

Toolchain and tool directories are bound read-only at their *identical* host paths (not remapped), so cargo/rustup/etc. resolve paths exactly as the host has them configured, while everything else under `$HOME` stays invisible. `CAGE_BIN` is a tmpfs, not a real bind, populated only by whatever's added via `tool_binds`.

Argument order is meaningful and fixed by `build_bwrap_args`: base isolation → workspace → toolchain → tools/rules → envs → `--` → the actual cage command (`c.cage_cmd`). Each `add_*` helper is kept intentionally small/short per the module's stated style convention (each helper "well under the length tier") — if extending, prefer adding a new `add_*` function over growing an existing one. Constants `CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR` come from `super::config` and must match whatever the in-cage code (proxy client, rules loader) expects at those exact paths — drift here breaks the sandboxed process silently rather than at build time.